        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local SEO</strong> is the practice of optimizing a business's online presence to attract customers from location-based searches. Unlike national SEO, it focuses on ranking in Google's Local Pack and local organic results within defined geographic areas — primarily through Google Business Profile optimization, NAP citation consistency, review management, and location-specific website content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Local search share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">46% of Google queries</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Key platform</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Business Profile</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you run a service business with a geographic footprint — a dental practice, a plumbing company, a law firm, a restaurant — local SEO is the highest-return marketing channel available. The people searching "dentist near me" or "emergency plumber [city]" are not browsing. They are ready to buy.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Local SEO?</h2>
        <p>Local SEO is a specialisation of search engine optimization focused on geographic visibility. Where traditional SEO competes for national or global rankings, local SEO competes for placement in two specific result types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The Local Pack (Map Pack):</strong> The 3-business block with a map that appears above organic results for location-intent queries. Powered primarily by Google Business Profile data and local signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Local organic results:</strong> The standard blue-link results that appear below the Local Pack, ranked on the same algorithmic factors as national SEO but weighted toward geographic relevance.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Google uses three primary factors to determine local rankings: <strong>Relevance</strong> (how well a business matches the query), <strong>Distance</strong> (proximity to the searcher), and <strong>Prominence</strong> (how well-known and trusted the business is across the web).</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Local search stats that matter</div>
          <p>76% of people who search for a nearby business on mobile visit within one day. 28% of local searches result in a purchase. The Local Pack appears in 93% of searches with local intent. These numbers explain why local SEO consistently outperforms paid search on cost-per-acquisition for service businesses.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Local SEO matters for service businesses</h2>
        <p>The business case for local SEO comes down to five compounding advantages:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>High-intent traffic.</strong> Someone searching "emergency HVAC repair near me" at 11pm is not researching — they are buying. Local search captures buyers at the moment of maximum intent, a quality paid ads rarely match at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Zero cost per click.</strong> Local Pack and local organic rankings deliver traffic without per-click costs. Unlike Google Ads, a top-3 local pack position costs the same whether it generates 2 clicks or 200 clicks per day.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding returns.</strong> Reviews generate more reviews. Citations build authority that makes new content rank faster. Each optimized signal compounds the others, creating a moat that widens over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile dominance.</strong> "Near me" searches have grown 500% in five years. Local results dominate mobile screens — the first 3 local pack results can occupy the entire above-the-fold area on a phone.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive market access.</strong> In most local markets, the majority of competitors do not maintain their local SEO consistently. A business that invests systematically over 6-12 months typically earns Local Pack position regardless of domain age or brand size.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Local SEO works</h2>
        <p>Google's local algorithm evaluates businesses across three independent but interacting signals:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-label">Relevance</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">GBP category + business description + website content + schema</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Distance</span>  <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">GPS location / IP address / search term geography</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Prominence</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Review count + rating + citation consistency + backlinks + web mentions</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># All three feed Google's Local Pack ranking algorithm</span>
        </div>

        <p>A business can be highly relevant and close to the searcher but rank poorly because it has few reviews and inconsistent citations — prominence drags down the other two. This is why local SEO requires coordinated effort across all signals, not just GBP optimization in isolation.</p>

        <h2 id="components">Key Local SEO components</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Component</th><th>What it involves</th><th>Impact on rankings</th></tr>
            </thead>
