                <td>High — direct prominence signal</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>On-page local SEO</strong></td>
                <td>Location keywords, city/service area pages, LocalBusiness schema, NAP on website</td>
                <td>Local organic rankings</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local link building</strong></td>
                <td>Chamber of commerce, local news coverage, sponsorships, local business associations</td>
                <td>Domain authority + prominence</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local content</strong></td>
                <td>Location-specific pages, neighborhood guides, local FAQ content</td>
                <td>Relevance + organic rankings</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local SEO vs traditional SEO — key differences</h2>
        <p>Both disciplines optimize for Google, but the signals, platforms, and tactics diverge significantly.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local SEO focuses on</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Google Business Profile (unique to local)</li>
              <li>NAP consistency across directories</li>
              <li>Customer reviews on multiple platforms</li>
              <li>Proximity as a ranking factor</li>
              <li>Local Pack in addition to organic</li>
              <li>Hyper-local content (neighborhood, city)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Traditional SEO focuses on</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Domain authority and backlink profile</li>
              <li>Content depth and topical authority</li>
              <li>National or global keyword rankings</li>
              <li>E-E-A-T signals</li>
              <li>Technical SEO at scale</li>
              <li>Core Web Vitals and page experience</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="getting-started">How to get started with Local SEO — 7 steps</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Claim and verify Google Business Profile.</strong> Go to business.google.com. Complete every section: business name, category (primary + secondary), address or service area, phone, website, hours, photos, business description. Verification typically takes 5-7 days by postcard or phone.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit NAP consistency.</strong> Use BrightLocal or Moz Local to scan your existing citations. Fix any address, phone number, or name variations before building new citations. Inconsistent data confuses Google and reduces trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Build core directory citations.</strong> Submit to Yelp, Apple Maps, Bing Places, Facebook, BBB, and the top 10-15 industry-specific directories for your category. Prioritize accuracy over quantity.</li>
          <li><strong>Establish a review generation process.</strong> Ask every satisfied customer for a Google review within 24 hours of service — via SMS or email with a direct link. Aim for a minimum of 5 new reviews per month. Never incentivise reviews (violates Google policy).</li>
          <li><strong>Optimize your website for local keywords.</strong> Include your city and service area naturally in title tags, H1s, and body copy. Add a LocalBusiness schema block to your homepage and location pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Create location-specific pages.</strong> If you serve multiple cities or neighborhoods, each deserves its own landing page with unique content. Do not create thin, template-identical pages — Google identifies and ignores them.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn local backlinks.</strong> Join your Chamber of Commerce. Sponsor a local event. Pitch your expertise to a local news outlet. One backlink from a local .gov or .edu source carries more local ranking weight than 20 generic directory links.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — review gating</div>
          <p>Review gating — asking customers to rate their experience privately first and only routing happy customers to Google — violates Google's review policies. Google has removed millions of reviews caught through gating behavior. Build reviews honestly by asking all customers equally, then responding to both positive and negative feedback publicly.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Local SEO mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating GBP setup as a one-time task</strong> — GBP rewards active businesses. Businesses that post weekly and respond to reviews within 48 hours consistently outrank those that set up once and abandon.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent NAP data</strong> — A phone number change left uncorrected in 30+ directories fragments your local authority. Audit every 6 months and after any business changes.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews</strong> — A single unanswered 1-star review loses more potential customers than the bad review itself. Respond to every review, especially negative ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating identical location pages</strong> — Copy-paste location pages with only the city name swapped are recognized as thin content. Each location page needs unique descriptions, local testimonials, and locally relevant information.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping local link building</strong> — Most local SEO guides focus only on GBP and citations. Local backlinks are the prominence signal that separates page-1 local organic rankings from page-3.</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking local pack rankings</strong> — Standard rank tracking tools miss Local Pack positions. Use Local Falcon or BrightLocal for geo-grid rank tracking to see your actual local visibility across your service area.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
